comprehensive:

OpenAPI
Files: openapi.yaml, openapi.json
Why: extremely common for REST/API-first repos, and the OpenAPI Initiative is still actively evolving the spec. I’d treat this as first-class, not “just YAML.” Sources: OpenAPI Initiative, OpenAPI spec
AsyncAPI
Files: asyncapi.yaml, asyncapi.json
Why: the event-driven counterpart to OpenAPI; increasingly relevant for Kafka/pubsub/websocket-heavy systems. Source: AsyncAPI docs
JSON Schema
Files: _.schema.json, schema-bearing JSON/YAML
Why: this is a major missing piece. A lot of modern config, API, and tooling ecosystems rely on JSON Schema validation. Source: JSON Schema
CUE
Files: .cue
Why: increasingly useful for config, validation, schema, and policy workflows. This is one of the strongest “new-ish but serious” additions. Source: CUE docs
Rego / OPA
Files: .rego
Why: policy-as-code is now common enough in infra/platform/security work to justify explicit support. Source: OPA docs
Helm Chart templating
Files: Chart.yaml, values.yaml, templates/_.yaml, templates/\*.tpl
Why: Helm charts are not just “YAML”; they’re effectively their own templating language/workflow. Source: Helm chart templates
Ansible
Files: playbook.yml, roles/\*\*, galaxy.yml
Why: if you want “ultimate workstation” coverage, Ansible is a notable omission. Source: Ansible Lint docs
Jsonnet
Files: .jsonnet, .libsonnet
Why: still common in infra/config-heavy environments.
Bicep
Files: .bicep
Why: if Azure is in scope, Bicep should probably be present.
Jupyter / notebooks
Files: .ipynb
Why: you mention notebooks under Python, but I’d elevate notebook tooling to a first-class concern because current GitHub usage keeps showing strong notebook growth. Source: GitHub Octoverse 2025
